ul.li: Ordered id corresponding to creation time of SSTables
Unordered id for avoiding collision of scnd_idx-* dirs

Single:
It would be fine to use a single u64 for all ids, since u64's value range is large enough.
Code organization:
Locate the id inside struct DB. Make struct LSMTree hold a circular reference back to DB.
Share id in an Arc<Mutex<_>>. Mutex is wasteful, since we are single-threaded.
Share id in an Arc<_>. Unsafely cast to `&mut` whenever incrementing the id.

Multiple:
Each LSM and the DB has its own id generaotr.
It's cheap to have multiple instances.
We go with multiple.

div.div:
We choose to always move each raw non-clonable `Datum` into Arc.
Disadvantages:
This is wasteful b/c these data are guaranteed to be used by exactly one thread.
One Arc costs 2 more usizes compared to a Box.
Each access requires an extra ptr hop. (Relevant mostly for the otherwise stack-only type of Datum::I64)
Modifying Arc's atomic counter would introduce memory barriers. But, iff we ensure to never clone() the Arc and always move it, we can prevent this cost.
Advantages:
We reduce the variety of types. Hence we reduce possible conversions among types. A merged iterator item is either `(&K, &V)` or `Result<(K, V)>`.
